Ciber's (CBR) CEO Michael Boustridge on Q1 2016 Results - Earnings Call Transcript | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Ciber's (CBR) CEO Michael Boustridge on Q1 2016 Results - Earnings Call TranscriptMay. 5.16 | About: CIBER, Inc. (CBR) CIBER, Inc. (NYSE:CBR)
Q1 2016 Results Earnings Conference Call
May 05, 2016, 08:30 AM ET
Executives
Scott Kozak - Direct of Investor Relations
Michael Boustridge - President and Chief Executive Officer
Christian Mezger - Chief Financial Officer
Analysts
Marco Rodriguez - Stonegate Capital Markets
Brian Kinstlinger - Maxim Group
Operator
Greetings and welcome to the Ciber Inc. First Quarter 2016 Earnings Conference Call. At this time, all participants are in listen-only mode. A brief question-and-answer session will follow the formal presentation. [Operator Instructions] As a reminder, this conference is being recorded.
I would now like to turn the conference over to your host, Mr. Scott Kozak, Direct of Investor Relations. Thank you, Mr. Kozak. You may begin.
Scott Kozak
Thank you, operator. Good morning, everyone. My name is Scott Kozak, Senior Director of Investor Relations at Ciber. Welcome to Ciber’s first quarter 2016 earnings conference call. With me today are Michael Boustridge, our President and Chief Executive Officer and Christian Mezger, our CFO.
Before turning the call over to Michael, I will remind you that some of our prepared comments and responses to your questions will constitute forward-looking statements. These forward-looking statements are subject to risks and uncertainties that could cause actual results to differ materially from those expressed or implied by such statements. Such risks and uncertainties include, but are not limited to those factors set forth in today’s news release and discussed under the risk factors section of our Annual Report on Form 10-K and Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q as well as other SEC filings.
Also during this call, we will reference certain non-GAAP financial measures that we believe provide useful information for investors. We have included reconciliations of those measures to GAAP measures in our news release and on the Investor Relations section of our website, ciber.com. Today’s discussion will be on a continuing operations basis. Please refer to our SEC filings on Form 10-K, Form 10-Q and 8-K for a recap of historical comparisons.
With that, it is my pleasure to turn the call over to Ciber’s President and CEO, Michael Boustridge. Michael?
Michael Boustridge
Thank you, Scott. Good morning, everyone and welcome to our call. Although there were several positive developments in our first quarter, this was a challenging period for Ciber reflecting the ongoing impact of issues I have discussed with you before, largely involving the time it is taking our company to recover from years of under investment in key businesses and new offerings
Although second quarter revenues and profits were likely to be impacted as well, our continued focus in these areas has begun to show meaningful improvement and bookings and I remain confident that our second half will show topline results and good profitability.
In the first quarter, we continued to benefit from backlog in North America reflecting weaker bookings during the first half of 2015. I will talk more in a moment about what we believe is a positive turning point for those bookings.
Reflecting recent industry trends involving [Indiscernible] compression we also absorbed pricing pressure from some of our largest customers as we successfully retained their business. We also faced pressures in our international business where 2015 bookings were below 2014 levels throughout most of the last year leaving us with fewer revenue opportunities early in 2016.
In addition, business in the U.K. has not recovered quickly as we expected and we are facing what we believe are short terms staffing recruitment issues in some of our larger country markets. I will return to these issues later in my comments.
Looking forward, we believe Ciber’s current pipeline bookings and book-to-bill ratios will lead to better revenue results in the second half of the year. Our pipeline of qualified opportunities which we consider cross based [ph] closing to become sign deals [ph] grew 8% sequentially in the first quarter, providing a good indication of our market stabilization.

Going forward, I will provide bookings rather than pipeline to give you a sense of the revenue momentum. I told you that I would provide net process that became comfortable with that company’s ability to produce and forecast them accurately. And I bring bookings to be as best indicator of our future performance.
First quarter 2016 marked one of our strongest year-over-year bookings increases in recent periods. These gains were driven by investment in product development, sales and marketing as well as last year’s portfolio of rationalization effort.
Ciber’s first quarter bookings which included signed customer contract is fixed to produce revenue in the near future rose 6% year-over-year. Bookings were particularly strong in North America. These increased bookings led to a one to one book-to-bill ratio in North America in the first quarter and 1.0 internationally. This is the first period where we have achieved an international book-to-bill ratio at or above one since the fourth quarter of 2014.
We expect increased year-over-year bookings and book-to-bill ratios at around or above 1.0 in the first half providing the foundation of Ciber to achieve future revenue growth and marginal improvement.
The time it take bookings to float a revenue obviously differs from different types of business though we estimate that more than half of their bookings will flow to the topline sometime in fiscal 2016.
As I have said many times, we understand that our company must resume its past to revenue growth in order to increase margins, expand profit and generate greater levels of cash. We took actions in 2015 to accomplish these results including focussing on our core offerings and despite tightly defined colors, solidifying our reputation in the fast growing cloud implementation and reducing Ciber momentum and delivering on our Ciber transformation services model.
We also have instructed Ciber’s board of directors to appoint members who had the deep technology expertise, business strategy and customer focus needed to achieve our primary objective of delivering long term growth and enhanced share holder value.
I will leave the detailed discussion of the reported results to Christian. I particularly wanted to highlight efforts outside the Ciber momentum. As we believe industry rich portfolio solutions to our verticals like retail, utilities and local government will also produce good return.
As one example, we are introducing an in the box concept for retail utility. This product enables companies to offer new, disruptive business proposition to the customers with time to view [ph] spilling and dynamic retail pricing.
We expect strong interest for customers that want to adapt a pay as you go model in the cloud to avoid heavy start up cost and back office application. Another example is our go-to-market strategy around digitalization in the retail industry.
Amongst other features this strategy provides businesses with access to long term information about the customer’s behaviour. A case in point is a retail template implementation for this year, a German retail housekeeper provider that is part of the Mackeson [ph].
Our produce scope included a phase 1 implementation in Norway which is already completed and phase 2 which when completes [ph] implementations in the U.K. and Germany. When complete, the Ciber implementation would allow [Indiscernible] to implement benefits from one global ERP Solutions such as having one consolidated view of their financial performance in all countries and optimizing the worldwide purchases.
Over the last 12 months we’ve also been working to standardise outdated legacy bonus plans in Europe. Ciber is moving towards globally aligned compensation systems that will allow our employees to next March payout tied to our company performance. As we carry out the challenging but necessary program changes, we are experiencing higher than normal employee turnover, which will continue to have a negative impact on our revenue growth and profitability.

We started this work in early 2015. This is not an easy transition as we focus on the quality of service to our customers who are balancing the needs of our employees who are critical to the success of our company. Let me turn now to an update on Ciber momentum.
Market reaction to the talk [ph] continues to be strong; importantly we are finding that modernization is not just the legacy application. Technology changes are appearing so quickly that even systems less than 10 years old need to be modernized to use the cloud. We have 19 Ciber invented proof-of-concept POCs in the market at present and we expect several additional POCs such as the engagement in Europe we announced in April that will generate fees to contribute to Ciber’s topline.
We believe these POCs proved it to works [ph] and are opening new opportunities for Ciber Momentum. For instance, the Ciber Momentum subscription that we signed in February partnering with a large diversified industrial company is executing well. We have provided great value to the customer demonstrating that the tool can accelerate and automate some important modernization script. A customer has just increased a modernization project with us for an additional $1.7 million engagement in managed services.
We expect that the customer will expand the Ciber Momentum engineering subscription to support that modernization effort. Our international transaction evolves the paid proof-of-concept for the European bank.
We are optimistic that we have signed an engagement to modernized and migrate their first application to a private cloud. Ciber Transformation Services also making an important progress in the large scale labor talent reengineering market.
Our first engagement is proceeding well with high customer satisfaction and the experience we've gain from this transaction pass the way for more extensive product launch.
Importantly, customers that tell us that Ciber Momentum and Ciber Transformation Services providing unique sales proposition, we will combined these offerings, we help our customers modernize both the legacy applications and their workforce.
Our investment effort continues, we added $2 million in the first quarter to the $7 million of spend over the prior 15 months to support product development marketing expenditures, proof-of-concept and start up cost behind our key offerings.
Ciber Momentum spending in particular remains on track to reach $5 million in 2016 up $1.5 million last year. These investments are absolutely critical to generate revenue streams beyond Ciber's legacy staffing and implementation business.
In addition to a keen focus on revenue growth we'll remain committed to controlling our GA overhead costs. When I spoke with you at -- I said that we will reduce GA expenses by $5 million in 2016.
While our first quarter 2016 corporate cost were high reflecting continued investment primary in the IT. I'm confident we were actually over achieved that $5 million goal in 2016 excluding an unavoidable increase in legal cost.
We must succeed the goal because despite our commitment to cut cost some expenses continue to significantly exceed our expectations. For example, we've a number of legacy legal actions related to contested contracts that have raised legal expenses significantly in 2015 and will cost even more in 2016.
Cost to file these claims contributes to an increase in legal expense from approximately $6 million in 2014 to $8 million last year as none of these matters can be resolved. We anticipate legal actions in 2016 could exceed $12 million.
As a business leader I'm shocked at some of the frivolous unfounded claims levied against Ciber. We have no choice but vigorously defend our company on behalf of our customers, our employees and our shareholders.

As one example, I have told you about a sizeable project in the U.K. that we decided to end early after the contract that became terrible due to indefinite cost exposures.
This dispute with Century [Indiscernible] is still outstanding. A course a short term head to our financial results that will continue through the second quarter and it is also contributing to high legal expenses.
Exiting this contract was a painful decision to make, but I'm confident that was a correct move. Importantly, we have incurred no substantial contract litigation in 2016 since dramatically improved our processes for betting and managing our engagement.
Marketing has spent considerable effort and investment to reduce the likelihood of ongoing issues with current and respective transaction. In essence our company's goal is to sign no contract without been highly confident that we can deliver.
Regarding cash, Christian will provide a detailed discussion, but I wanted to reiterate our expectation for positive generation of cash from operations in 2016. We are also working to the best non-strategic operations.
Just this week we reach an agreement to sell our Australian operation to its management and we continue to evaluate additional divestitures. As a reminder, we have performed total shareholder return and individual total shareholder return analysis for entire business.
We have created a capital allocation strategy, we've recently engage in investment bank to help us with potential transaction and now we're ready recommendations to our Boards of Directors at our next meeting later this month.
As I continue to update even our performance throughout 2016, I believe our second half results will show increased revenues and cash which came in from a high booking, targeted investments, and focused on cost containment.
As I told before revenue growth is a key to expanding margins in this competitive market. Ciber must continue its transformation towards a broader set of offerings involving Ciber Momentum, Ciber Transformation Services, Talent Services and our industry verticals that takes advantage of the skill set of our talented employees.
As we execute on our positive bookings and strategic assets allocation we will achieve revenue growth, good margin and strong cash flow. In conclusion, management and the board are aligned on the actions necessary to achieve a multi-year turnaround of Ciber and accomplish our goals of significantly increasing shareholder value.
These actions are reigniting revenue growth in all areas of the business through re-investment and revenue producers and the launch of new and innovative product. Improving operating margins by eliminating harmful legacy incentive plan and leveraging our global operating model to deliver standardized repeatable premier offering.
Resulting long standing legal challenges while leveraging our disciplined structure processed and paid to strengthen customer communications and contract management to prevent new issues before they can begin.
Exiting non-strategic businesses and generating positive operating cash flow and improving our financial position. I will now hand the call over to Christian.
Christian Mezger
Thank you, Michael and good morning everyone. I will provide a few highlights for the most recent quarter. Overall revenue of $175 million was disappointing leaving [ph] currency which negatively impacted the topline by about $5 million on a year-over-year basis.
Our first quarter revenue in North America was primarily driven by lower booking levels during the first half of last year. As previously mentioned, bookings in Talent Services were negatively impacted by multiple years on the investment prior to 2015. It takes a considerable amount of time to transfer revenues after years of neglect.

[Indiscernible] for the recent year-over-year growth in North America bookings. A 7% increase in the fourth quarter of 2015 and an 11% increase in the first quarter of 2016. In the international segment, revenues were impacted by our exit of certain contracts particularly Sanctuary Housing in the U.K. that we discussed previously. In addition, lower 2015 bookings also clocked lower revenues.
On a positive note, year-over-year first quarter bookings improved in the international segment. It is critical that we sustained bookings growth in 2016 to achieve revenue growth and improved profitability during the second half of the year. We believe our investment and focus on generating bookings has started to pay off. Its reflected in year-over-year improvement in bookings during the first quarter.
As Michael has previously said our road to sustainable improvement in margin, profit and cash generation also depends on the additional cost reduction we have taken and will continue to affect in the near term. We have initiated headcount reductions since the end of the quarter.
Lower operating margins does not only reduce revenue but also continued investment and higher litigation [ph] expenses from contested legacy contract. Each investment program is vigorously monitored to ensure its good turn.
We had cash usage in the most recent period as it's difficult for Ciber’s first quarter and it was substantially lower than the usage during the year ago period. We are highly focussed on generating positive operating cash for the year.
We reached agreement in principle to sell our Australian operation to its management. This business has limited [Indiscernible] and has geographically isolated from the rest of Ciber and an exit will improve our focus of core operation. We had an $86 million non-cash impairment charge in the first quarter related to our international segment. The sustained decline and the Company’s stock price earlier this year led to a goodwill impairment assessment. The review [ph] concluded that the fair value of goodwill in our international segment was below its current value.
Overall, despite challenges in the first half of the year we believe we are on track to deliver a continued book-to-bill improvement, revenue growth, cost reduction and positive operating margins during the second half of 2016.
Turning to company’s financial results. Revenue in the first quarter of 2016 was $175 million, down 10% sequentially and 11% year-over-year both in constant currency. When measured in U.S. dollars, revenue was down 10% sequentially and down 13% year-over-year. 
Gross margin was 23.3% down from 25.6% in the prior year, primarily due to lower revenues and pricing pressure. SG&A expense in constant currency was $49 million for the quarter, up 10% year-over-year and down 8% sequentially.
SG&A increased compared to last year due to higher corporate cost and previously mentioned investment. Corporate cost grew up both year-over-year and sequentially. The year-over-year increase was driven by higher legal expenses, transition costs associated with outsourcing Ciber's IT and cost related to our SAP implementation.
The other [ph] two items also drove the increase in sequential corporate cost. As mentioned before, we addressed the increasing cost with additional headcount reduction. Adjusted operating loss from continuing operations totaled $8.5 million in the quarter. Adjusted net loss from continuing operations in the first quarter before amortization and restructuring charges was $10 million or $0.13 per share compared to net income of $4 million or $0.05 per share in the year ago quarter.
On a GAAP basis net loss from continuing operations was $97 million or $1.21 per share including the non-cash goodwill impairment charge. Looking at our North America segment, revenue performance in the first quarter was impacted by tightening client budget that led to [Indiscernible] spending reduction and pricing pressure, which we have seen across the IT services industry.

Revenue was $100 million down 6% year-over-year and down 8% sequentially. Growth in our input practise and the addition of Ciber Transformation Service revenues were more than offset by year-over-year declines in the rest of the businesses.
Talent Service revenues in North America were down also the rate of decline were slow due to the investments we made in the business. We expect these investments will return this business to revenue and profits growth in the second half of 2016.
In addition, coming up at strong 2015 revenues in our Oracle practice were down year-over-year in the first quarter as we completed specific projects. While we saw fewer available and signed deals spent in 2015 and an associated increase in competition, we did record strong Oracle booking in the first quarter of 2016.
North America gross profit margin was 25.1% down from 27.5% in last years first quarter and down from 26.7% in the fourth quarter. Our gross margins were negatively impacted by decline in revenues in Oracle and ADM businesses.
Gross profits in these practices was also impacted by bill rate decline and higher bench [ph] cost resulting from contract negotiations delays and pricing pressures. On the other hand, our input business saw improved gross profit margins due to across the market revenue growth.
SG&A expense was $18.4 million down 3% year-over-year and up 2% sequentially. Year-over-year declines were driven by previous cost reductions partially offset by the necessary investment Ciber Momentum, Ciber Transformation Services and Talent Services.
Operating margins of 6.6% was down 290 basis points compared to the year ago period and down 330 basis points sequentially. The decline was driven by lower gross margins resulting from revenue decline. Our strong bookings in the first quarter and our expectations that book-to-bill trends will continue to be strong, give us confidence that we will achieve revenue and profitability growth in the second half of 2016.
I will now discuss the international sector. First quarter revenues were $76 million down 16% in constant currency compared to a year ago quarter due to declines across most of our operations. In U.S. dollars the year-over-year decline was 21%. As in previous quarters the U.K. were half of the year-over-year revenue decline. The shortfall was partially offset by healthy growth in our German Managed Services.
Sequential revenues in our international segment were down 12% on a constant currency basis and 13% on a U.S. dollar basis. Sequentially revenues were impacted by seasonality and a decline in the number of billable consultants.
Gross profit margin was 20.6% in the first quarter down 270 basis points year-over-year and down 250 basis points sequentially. Gross margin declines are directly related to lower revenue and the limited flexibility to make timely adjustments to our labor cost base.
SG&A was $16.6 million during the first quarter, up 3% year-over-year due to investment to Ciber Momentum. We had an operating loss from continuing operations of $1 million. To restore international operations to acceptable levels of profitability, we must continue to grow bookings to increase revenue and gross profit. My last year’s restructuring addressed the realignment to the global operating model. We are accelerating other aggressive actions to meet our overhead structure to lower our revenues.
Also, our delivery mix of billable hours delivered EMEA and offshore continues to improve. As a company, we exceeded 25% of billable hours delivered offshore in the first quarter. I will now discuss cash and our balance sheet.
We ended the quarter with a cash balance of $80 million compared to $20 million at year end 2015. Cash used in operating activities and continued operations was $3 million in the first quarter of 2016 compared with cash usage of $34 million in the first quarter of 2015.

Changes in working capital primarily contributed to the overall improvement. This included a $9 million sequential decrease in our accounts receivable provision compared to relatively flat receivables in 2015 and a more modest reduction in accrued [ph] competition.
Total DSO was 71 days at the end of the first quarter compared to the 63 days and the year ago period and 64 days at the end of the fourth quarter. This temporary increase was mainly driven by rapidly declining revenues in the quarter. At the same time, we have seen an improvement in the ageing of our receivables both on a year-over-year and sequential basis.
Our cash usage in the first quarter included investments of $2 million. The outstanding balance on the credit facility is $40 million at the end of March 31, 2016 compared to $33 million at year end.
Capital expenditures were $5 million in the quarter. We had now a run rate for core capital expenditures to about $2 million per quarter. The increments of CapEx in the first quarter is related to the implementation of the new ERP and HRM systems and to a lesser extent spending for Ciber Momentum.
In summary, while it was a difficult quarter we are encouraged by the increase in bookings that are expected to improve our value performance during the second half of 2016. We are taken decisive actions to lower our G&A cost structure to improve profitability and cash flow during the second half of this year. We expect to over achieve to $5 million goal to lower G&A in 2016 excluding the potential impact of higher legal cost.
Lastly, with our evaluations completed, we are now ready to make recommendations on the divestiture of non strategic businesses at the next meeting of our board of directors in mid-May.
With that, I would like to open it up for Q&A. Operator, please give the instructions.
