Transcript by:

CIBER, Inc. (CBR)Q3 2015 Earnings Conference CallOctober 29, 2015 08:30 AM ETExecutivesHeather Pollard - Director, FinanceMichael Boustridge - President and CEOChristian Mezger - EVP and CFOAnalystsJuan Bejarano - Noble FinancialBrian Kinstlinger - Maxim GroupMarco Rodriguez - Stonegate Capital MarketsPresentationOperatorCompare to:Previous Statements by CBR» Ciber's (CBR) CEO Michael Boustridge Discusses Q2 2015 Results - Earnings Call Transcript» CIBER's (CBR) CEO Michael Boustridge on Q1 2015 Results - Earnings Call Transcript» Ciber's (CBR) CEO Michael Boustridge on Q4 2014 Results - Earnings Call TranscriptGreetings and welcome to the Ciber, Inc. Third Quarter 2015 Earnings Conference Call. At this time, all participants are in listen-only mode. A question-and-answer session will follow the formal presentation. [Operator Instructions] As a reminder, this conference is being recorded.It is now my pleasure to introduce your host, Heather Pollard. Please go ahead.Heather PollardThank you, operator. Good morning, everyone. My name is Heather Pollard, Director of Finance at Ciber. Welcome to Ciber's third quarter 2015 earnings conference call. With me today are Michael Boustridge, our President and Chief Executive Officer and Christian Mezger, our CFO.Before turning the call over to Michael, I will remind you that some of our prepared comments and responses to your questions will constitute forward-looking statements. These forward-looking statements are subject to risks and uncertainties that could cause actual results to differ materially from those expressed or implied by such statements. Such risks and uncertainties include, but are not limited to those factors set forth in today's news release and discussed under the risk factors section of our quarterly report on Form 10-Q and our annual report on Form 10-K as well as other SEC filings.Also during this call, we will reference certain non-GAAP financial measures that we believe provide useful information for investors. We have included reconciliations of those measures to GAAP measures in our news release and on the Investor Relations section of our website, ciber.com. Today's discussion will be on a continuing operations basis. Please refer to our SEC filings on Form 10-Q and 8-K for a recap of historical comparisons.With that, it is my pleasure to turn the call over to Ciber's President and CEO, Michael Boustridge. Michael?Michael BoustridgeThank you, Heather. Good morning, everyone and welcome to our call. Ciber's transformation continues. Our third quarter results very clearly reflect both the costs and the benefit of our plans to be a leader in staffing, services and software as a service delivery. We continue to execute against the strategy, making the balance investments listed to accelerate our long-term company's growth. We are concentrating our efforts on a specific range of service offerings, process improvements and talent enhancements that I initiated when I joined Ciber last year. Specifically, we have focused on five tightly defined pillars. We announced our new SaaS offering [indiscernible] which includes the ability to grow rapidly, increase profits and transform our customer's business.This offering has the potential to double the margins of our existing business and create deeper, more valuable and long lasting current relationships. We used our Ciber transformation services offering with an iconic win at HP. Combined the last two points, we linked Ciber Momentum and Ciber transformation services together to enhance the benefits to both offerings. We added a number of leaders in Ciber executives with specific skillset and knowledge needed to support Ciber Momentum and Ciber transformation services. While these additional resources may raise our SG&A costs, Ciber Momentum and Ciber transformation services require a specific go-to market approach.And lastly we continue to build resource in India. We added 70 actual wells this quarter and made trading number billable hours delivered offshore to 25%. As Ciber Momentum penetrates the market, we expect to dramatically increase our offshore talent. While our mid-term results reflect the cost of these investments, we remain committed to achieving 6% to 8% operating margins with investments by the second half of 2016. Our recent progress in Ciber Momentum and Ciber transformation services reinforces my confidence in the achievability of these results. I cannot stress enough that this level of profitability will not materialize without significant investments. Christian will provide details on our spending in his remarks, but I would like to update the metric I began last quarter.In my last quarter remarks, I noted that we have invested $5 million over the 12 months in new market and offering development. We accelerated our pace of investment last quarter, spending $2 million, bringing the total to $7 million. We continue to expect the high level investments over the near-term as our spending patterns evolve beyond product development to include marketing expenditures, customer proof of concept and ultimately startup cost for wins associated for both Ciber Momentum and Ciber transformation services.As you know, our service offerings are focused amongst five pillars. Our newest pillar, software as a service delivery delivered the Ciber compliance suite on a SaaS model and launched Ciber Momentum beginning with North America this past quarter. Ciber Momentum is our automated platform for application normalization which we believe will free customers from the unsustainable cost and operating models associated with legacy applications. Every survey we have seen indicates application normalizations as a top priority for CIO. Ciber Momentum enable CIOs to attain the business processes that define the company while delivering the next generation application that takes advantages of the cost and benefits of cloud delivering models and an ability to show commodity technologies and readily available talent pools.Our goal is to be among the market leaders in application modernization. We know that we are not the only competitor in this field and we are not currently the largest. We are the only company however with a market differentiated technology which gives us Ciber Momentum product at least over the competition.Read the rest of this transcript for free on seekingalpha.com

































